    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5fb49d32-cb99-468e-978e-1ba7363d7733",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 4-year-old girl brought to clinic by her mother in the late afternoon after three days of worsening cough, low-grade fever, and noisy breathing. She looks tired but alert, clinging to a stuffed rabbit and leaning against her mother between bursts of coughing. Her face is mildly flushed, her nose is runny, and she occasionally breathes through an open mouth because of nasal congestion. During the visit she has a frequent harsh cough that is worse after activity and at night, and she becomes briefly fussy when asked to take deep breaths.\n\nAt home, {patientName} attends preschool, enjoys picture books, toy kitchen games, and chasing bubbles with her older cousin in the backyard. She lives with both parents and a school-aged brother in a nonsmoking home. The family has a pet cat, and she spends much of her day in close contact with other children at preschool, where several classmates recently had colds. Her parents describe her as usually energetic, playful, and social, but over the last few days she has preferred cuddling on the couch and taking extra naps.\n\nHer mother reports that the illness started with a runny nose and sneezing, then progressed to a dry cough that became more productive-sounding. Overnight coughing has interrupted sleep for both {patientName} and her parents. She has been drinking fluids in small amounts, eating less than usual, and saying that her chest \"feels funny,\" though she cannot describe it clearly because of her age. There has been no cyanosis, no choking episode, and no known aspiration event.\n\nThe family is attentive and engaged, with her mother carefully tracking temperatures and fluid intake and her father alternating caregiving after work. {patientName} is comforted by familiar routines, cartoons, and being held. There are no social concerns about neglect or unsafe housing, and her vaccinations are reported to be up to date for age. Overall, she appears like a preschool child with an acute respiratory illness who is mildly ill but still interactive and consolable."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ee375fff-20b6-4135-b6bf-31530fc9e3e9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has been generally healthy with normal growth and development and no chronic cardiopulmonary disease. She has no history of asthma diagnosis, prior pneumonia, or hospitalization for respiratory illness. Her parents report occasional viral colds since starting preschool, which is typical for her age. She has never required home oxygen or regular inhaled medications.\n\nThe current illness began about 3 days ago with rhinorrhea, sneezing, and a low-grade fever, followed by a worsening cough and mild shortness of breath when active. Oral intake is mildly reduced, but urine output remains present. There is no history of prematurity, congenital lung disease, foreign body aspiration, or exposure to tobacco smoke. No recent travel is reported. Her brother recently had a similar cold that resolved without complications.\n\nHome treatment has included fluids, honey-free warm drinks appropriate to family practice, rest, and acetaminophen given by her mother for fever with partial relief. Because of persistent nighttime cough and mildly noisy breathing, the family sought medical evaluation."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
